text: 6/n I guess that's what I want to end with. Math is done by people, in particular social and cultural contexts. Even what gets defined as math is dictated by this. And so by tugging at those, we might be able to enlarge who gets to do math and what math "counts."

text: 5/n Debates over the four color theorem's proof using computers, or current debates over Mochizuki's ABC conjecture, remind me that at least in some way, mathematical knowledge is at least in some way socially constructed. It isn't as easy as calling strikes and balls.
bbox_coords: NA NA NA NA NA NA NA NA

text: 4/n One merely needs to read Amir Alexander's _Infinitesimal_ to see how mathematical ideas were embedded in and propped up larger social and political systems -- and debates over them were actually debates over these systems. Proper ways of knowing were debated.

text:
3/n One can't help accept that that is true now - but looking at a slew of different factors (race being one of them). 

But ways of knowing also isn't immutable. What constitutes logic and proof have morphed over time - and intersect with the dominant culture.

text:
